{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778701002,"nonce":"ZT8JRrNmJsiEWhLLG9SGCz7tVsY=","message":"## Post-go velocity lag is filter-bound, not damping-induced\n\nForward velocity profiles from trained models show a post-go acceleration lag of ~3–5 timesteps (~30–50 ms) before velocity ramps up. This is **not a controller pathology** — it is the first-order force-filter step response, an unavoidable feature of the plant.\n\n**Analytic step response** (unit force command at t=0, dt=10 ms, τ_rise = τ_decay = 50 ms):\n\n| step (post-go) | t (ms) | F/u | v (m/s) |\n|---:|---:|---:|---:|\n| 1 | 10 | 0.20 | 0.0020 |\n| 2 | 20 | 0.36 | 0.0054 |\n| 3 | 30 | 0.49 | 0.0097 |\n| 4 | 40 | 0.59 | 0.0147 |\n| 5 | 50 | 0.67 | 0.0199 |\n\nAt v = 0 damping force is zero, so damping does **not** explain the t = 0+ lag — damping only constrains peak velocity and sustained force. The lag is the filter floor: regardless of network command, applied force reaches only ~63% of target by step 5.\n\nSmoothness and pre-go-motor-mask penalties can add a few steps on top of the physics floor, but neither is the dominant mechanism — the lag appears even in cells with only one of those penalties active.\n\n**Implication for interpretation:** comparisons of velocity-onset latency across training methods or adversary classes should be read against this filter floor. Differences smaller than ~3 timesteps may be entirely explained by control-cost or smoothness-penalty differences interacting with the filter, not by genuine differences in feedforward planning.\n\n**Decision records** (filed this session):\n- \\`a04711e\\` — damping k = 10 N·s/m (biomechanically defensible; cs2019's k=0.1 is the outlier).\n- \\`08c49e3\\` — force-filter τ = 50 ms (consistent with literature consensus; exact match to de Brouwer 2020).\n\n**Related sweep:** \\`2e5f643\\` (existing damping calibration retraining proposal, currently deferred).","files":null}]}